\section{Abstract}

This report presents a comprehensive AI/ML-driven solution for Digital Terrain Model (DTM) generation and optimized drainage network design using drone-captured LiDAR point cloud data. The proposed system addresses the challenge of delineating natural surface-water flow paths, predicting waterlogging hotspots, and designing cost-effective drainage infrastructure for densely populated village (abadi) areas. The pipeline integrates classical geospatial algorithms with machine learning classifiers (Random Forest, XGBoost) and deep learning (PointNet) to achieve robust terrain characterization. Our approach produces OGC-compliant outputs including Cloud-Optimized GeoTIFFs (COG) and GeoPackages (GPKG), suitable for direct integration with GIS platforms deployed by Panchayati Raj institutions.

\textbf{Keywords:} Digital Terrain Model, LiDAR, Point Cloud Classification, Drainage Network Design, Machine Learning, XGBoost, Hydrological Analysis, Waterlogging Prediction, OGC Standards.

\newpage

\section{Introduction}

\subsection{Background and Motivation}

The SVAMITVA (Survey of Villages and Mapping using Imagery and Technology for Abadi) scheme has enabled large-scale generation of high-resolution aerial imagery and LiDAR point cloud data for rural Indian villages. However, transforming this raw point cloud data into actionable geospatial intelligence for village planning remains a significant challenge. The absence of automated tools for Digital Terrain Model (DTM) creation and drainage network design forces engineers to rely on manual processing, which is time-consuming, error-prone, and inadequately scaled for the 6.5 lakh villages in India.

Waterlogging and inadequate drainage in abadi areas result in annual flood losses estimated at Rs. 15,000 crores across the country. Traditional drainage design relies on field surveys and approximate calculations, often leading to undersized or misaligned channels. The integration of AI/ML techniques offers a transformative approach: automated terrain analysis, predictive waterlogging modelling, and optimized hydraulic design---all within a reproducible, scalable pipeline.

\subsection{Problem Statement}

The objective of this research is to develop a data-driven DTM creation pipeline using drone point cloud datasets, combined with AI/ML-based waterlogging prediction and optimized drainage network design for densely inhabited village (abadi) areas. Specifically, the system must:

\begin{enumerate}[noitemsep]
	\item \textbf{Classify ground points} from raw LiDAR data using a hybrid morphological-ML approach;
	\item \textbf{Generate a high-resolution DTM} (0.5 m) suitable for hydrological analysis;
	\item \textbf{Delineate natural surface-water flow paths} and identify low-lying zones;
	\item \textbf{Predict waterlogging hotspots} using terrain-derived ML features;
	\item \textbf{Design an optimized drainage network} with hydraulic sizing and cost estimation.
\end{enumerate}

The pipeline must produce GIS-ready outputs compliant with OGC standards (COG, GPKG, LAS 1.4).

\subsection{Objectives}

\begin{itemize}
	\item Develop an automated three-stage ground classification pipeline combining PDAL-based morphological filters (SMRF, CSF) with Random Forest refinement;
	\item Implement IDW interpolation with Gaussian smoothing for DTM generation from classified ground points;
	\item Perform hydrological analysis using pysheds to compute flow direction, accumulation, and Topographic Wetness Index (TWI);
	\item Train an XGBoost classifier for waterlogging prediction using terrain features;
	\item Design a minimum spanning tree (MST) optimized drainage network using Manning's equation for hydraulic sizing;
	\item Generate all outputs in OGC-compliant formats.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Scope and Limitations}

This work focuses on Gujarat state datasets (SVAMITVA) as proof-of-concept. The methodology is transferable to other states with similar LiDAR coverage. Key limitations include:
\begin{itemize}
	\item Lack of ground-truth validation data for waterlogging events;
	\item Dependency on QGIS-bundled PDAL binaries for Windows compatibility;
	\item Computational requirements for processing 160M+ point datasets.
\end{itemize}

\newpage

\section{Literature Review}

\subsection{Point Cloud Classification}

Ground classification from LiDAR point clouds has been extensively studied. The \textbf{Simple Morphological Filter (SMRF)} (Pingel et al., 2013) remains a widely adopted approach due to its computational efficiency and robustness in flat terrain. The \textbf{Cloth Simulation Filter (CSF)} (Zhang et al., 2016) provides an alternative by simulating a cloth falling onto the terrain surface to distinguish ground from objects.

Recent advances incorporate machine learning. \textbf{Random Forest classifiers} operating on geometric features (eigenvalue-based metrics, density, height above ground) have shown improved accuracy over purely morphological methods (Weinstein et al., 2020). \textbf{Deep learning approaches} such as PointNet (Qi et al., 2017) enable per-point semantic segmentation but require substantial training data and GPU resources.

This work adopts a hybrid approach: SMRF as the primary filter, with Random Forest refinement on 12 geometric features computed via eigendecomposition.

\subsection{Digital Terrain Model Generation}

DTM generation from ground-classified points involves spatial interpolation. \textbf{Inverse Distance Weighting (IDW)} is a deterministic method where elevation values are weighted inversely by distance from interpolation points. \textbf{Kriging} provides a stochastic alternative with uncertainty quantification. Recent work favors \textbf{TIN-based interpolation} for preserving sharp terrain features (Argun et al., 2021).

Output standards have evolved toward \textbf{Cloud-Optimized GeoTIFFs (COGs)} as recommended by OGC for efficient cloud storage and streaming. This work implements IDW interpolation with Gaussian smoothing, exported as COG.

\subsection{Hydrological Analysis}

Terrain hydrology proceeds from depression-filled Digital Elevation Models. The \textbf{Wang and Liu algorithm} (2007) is the standard method for depression filling. \textbf{D8 flow direction} assigns each cell to one of eight downhill neighbors, enabling flow accumulation computation. \textbf{Topographic Wetness Index (TWI)} combines slope and flow accumulation to quantify wetness potential:
\begin{equation}
	\text{TWI} = \ln\left(\frac{A_s}{\tan\beta}\right)
\end{equation}
where $A_s$ is the specific catchment area and $\beta$ is the slope angle.

This work implements the complete pysheds workflow: fill $\rightarrow$ flow direction $\rightarrow$ accumulation $\rightarrow$ TWI $\rightarrow$ stream extraction.

\subsection{Waterlogging Prediction}

Machine learning models for flood prediction typically use terrain-derived features. \textbf{XGBoost} has demonstrated superior performance on imbalanced flood datasets (Tehrone et al., 2020) due to its ability to handle scale-positive weights. Key features include TWI, TPI (Topographic Position Index), curvature, and distance to streams.

A major challenge is label scarcity---we address this using terrain-heuristic pseudo-labeling: points with TWI $\ge$ 8, TPI $\le$ -0.3, and slope $\le$ 2$^\circ$ are labeled as waterlogging-prone.

\subsection{Drainage Network Design}

Optimal drainage design requires solving a network optimization problem. The \textbf{Minimum Spanning Tree (MST)} approach connects waterlogging hotspots to outlet points while minimizing total excavation cost. Hydraulic sizing uses \textbf{Manning's equation}:
\begin{equation}
	Q = \frac{1}{n} A R^{2/3} S^{1/2}
\end{equation}
where $n$ is Manning's roughness, $A$ is cross-sectional area, $R$ is hydraulic radius, and $S$ is channel slope.

The \textbf{Rational Method} ($Q = C \cdot i \cdot A$) estimates peak discharge from catchment areas. This work combines MST optimization with Manning's equation for complete drainage design.

