The system uses a configuration file (\texttt{config.yaml}) to manage all parameters, enabling reproducible runs without code modification.

\bigskip

The pipeline consists of 6 sequential stages:

\begin{enumerate}
    \item \textbf{Data Inspection} - Extract metadata from LAS/LAZ files
    \item \textbf{Ground Classification} - SMRF, CSF, Random Forest
    \item \textbf{DTM Generation} - IDW interpolation to COG
    \item \textbf{Hydrological Analysis} - Flow direction, TWI
    \item \textbf{Waterlogging Prediction} - XGBoost ML model
    \item \textbf{Drainage Design} - MST optimization, Manning's equation
\end{enumerate}

Outputs: DTM (COG), TWI/Flow (COG), Risk Map (COG), Drainage Network (GPKG)

\subsection{Stage 1: Data Inspection}

The pipeline begins by inspecting the input LAS/LAZ file to extract metadata:
\begin{itemize}
	\item Total point count and point density (points/m$^2$);
	\item Coordinate Reference System (CRS);
	\item Intensity range (detects zero-intensity data);
	\item Existing classification codes.
\end{itemize}

This stage identifies data quality issues (e.g., zero intensity, missing CRS) that inform downstream processing decisions.

\subsection{Stage 2: Ground Classification}

Ground classification employs a three-stage pipeline to handle the challenging Gujarat data:

\bigskip

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=1.2cm and 0.6cm, scale=0.9, transform shape]
		\node[stage] (smrf) {SMRF via PDAL};
		\node[stage, below=of smrf] (csf) {CSF via PDAL (Fallback)};
		\node[ml, right=of smrf] (rf) {Random Forest Refinement};
		\node[output, right=of rf] (out) {Classified LAS 1.4};

		\draw[arrow] (smrf) -- (rf);
		\draw[arrow] (csf) -- (rf);
		\draw[arrow] (rf) -- (out);

		\node[above=0.2cm of smrf, font=\small\bfseries] {Stage 2a};
		\node[above=0.2cm of csf, font=\small\bfseries] {Stage 2b};
		\node[above=0.2cm of rf, font=\small\bfseries] {Stage 2c};
	\end{tikzpicture}
	\caption{Three-stage Ground Classification Pipeline}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Stage 2a: SMRF via PDAL}\\
The Simple Morphological Filter operates on a moving window with adaptive thresholding:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \texttt{slope} = 0.15 (maximum terrain slope);
	\item \texttt{window} = 18.0 m (analysis window);
	\item \texttt{threshold} = 0.5 m (ground elevation difference);
	\item \texttt{scalar} = 1.25 (threshold multiplier).
\end{itemize}

PDAL is invoked via QGIS-bundled executables for Windows compatibility.

\textbf{Stage 2b: CSF Fallback}\\
Cloth Simulation Filter provides alternative classification for vegetated areas:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \texttt{resolution} = 0.5 m;
	\item \texttt{rigidness} = 3 (optimized for flat terrain);
	\item \texttt{class\_threshold} = 0.5.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Stage 2c: Random Forest Refinement}\\
A Random Forest classifier refines SMRF outputs using 12 geometric features:

\begin{enumerate}
	\item Eigenvalue sum
	\item Omnivariance
	\item Eigenentropy
	\item Anisotropy
	\item Planarity
	\item Linearity
	\item Surface variation
	\item Sphericity
	\item Verticality
	\item Density (1m radius)
	\item Z-range in neighbourhood
	\item Height above ground (approximate)
\end{enumerate}

Training uses SMRF labels as ground truth. For large datasets ($>$200k points), stratified subsampling with KNN propagation maintains accuracy while reducing computation time.

The classified point cloud is exported as LAS 1.4.

\subsection{Stage 3: DTM Generation}

The DTM is generated through the following steps:

\begin{enumerate}
	\item \textbf{Ground point extraction}: Filter classification = 2 (ground);
	\item \textbf{Grid construction}: Regular grid at configurable resolution (default 0.5 m);
	\item \textbf{IDW interpolation}:
	      \begin{equation}
		      Z(x,y) = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{z_i}{d_i^p}}{\sum_{i=1}^{n} \frac{1}{d_i^p}}
	      \end{equation}
	      where $p=2$ (power parameter), $d_i$ is distance, and $n$ neighbors within 5.0 m radius;
	\item \textbf{Gaussian smoothing}: $\sigma=1.0$ cells to reduce interpolation noise;
	\item \textbf{COG export}: Cloud-Optimized GeoTIFF with deflate compression and overview pyramids.
\end{enumerate}

\bigskip

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=1cm and 0.5cm, scale=0.85, transform shape]
		\node[data] (ground) {Ground Points (Class 2)};
		\node[stage] (grid) {Grid Construction};
		\node[stage] (idw) {IDW Interpolation};
		\node[stage] (smooth) {Gaussian Smoothing};
		\node[output] (cog) {COG Export (DTM)};

		\draw[arrow] (ground) -- (grid);
		\draw[arrow] (grid) -- (idw);
		\draw[arrow] (idw) -- (smooth);
		\draw[arrow] (smooth) -- (cog);
	\end{tikzpicture}
	\caption{DTM Generation Pipeline}
\end{figure}

\bigskip

DTM statistics (min/max elevation, relief, nodata percentage) are computed for quality assessment.

Terrain derivatives are computed simultaneously:
\begin{itemize}
	\item Slope (degrees)
	\item Aspect (degrees from North)
	\item Hillshade (illumination)
	\item Plan/Profile curvature
	\item Topographic Position Index (TPI)
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Stage 4: Hydrological Analysis}

Using the pysheds library, the pipeline performs:

\bigskip

\begin{figure}[htbp]
	\centering
	\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=0.6cm and 0.3cm, scale=0.8, transform shape]
		\node[stage] (fill) {Depression Filling};
		\node[stage] (dir) [below=of fill] {Flow Direction (D8)};
		\node[stage] (acc) [below=of dir] {Flow Accumulation};
		\node[stage] (twi) [below=of acc] {TWI Computation};
		\node[stage] (stream) [below=of twi] {Stream Extraction};
		\node[output] (outputs) [below=of stream] {COG + GPKG Outputs};

		\draw[arrow] (fill) -- (dir);
		\draw[arrow] (dir) -- (acc);
		\draw[arrow] (acc) -- (twi);
		\draw[arrow] (twi) -- (stream);
		\draw[arrow] (stream) -- (outputs);
	\end{tikzpicture}
	\caption{Hydrological Analysis Pipeline}
\end{figure}

\bigskip

Outputs include multiple COG rasters (flow direction, accumulation, TWI, slope) and vector layers (streams, catchments, depressions).

\subsection{Stage 5: Waterlogging Prediction}

Waterlogging prediction uses XGBoost with the following feature stack:

\begin{longtable}{lll}
	\toprule
	\textbf{Feature}        & \textbf{Description}                    & \textbf{Source}       \\
	\midrule
	Elevation (normalized)  & Z-score of elevation within village     & DTM                   \\
	Slope                   & Gradient magnitude (degrees)            & Terrain derivative    \\
	TWI                     & Topographic Wetness Index               & Hydrological analysis \\
	TPI                     & Topographic Position Index (15m window) & Terrain derivative    \\
	Plan Curvature          & Horizontal curvature                    & Terrain derivative    \\
	Profile Curvature       & Vertical curvature                      & Terrain derivative    \\
	Flow Accumulation (log) & Log-transformed accumulation            & Hydrological analysis \\
	Depression Depth        & Distance to nearest depression          & Terrain analysis      \\
	Distance to Stream      & Nearest stream channel distance         & Hydrological analysis \\
	\bottomrule
\end{longtable}

\bigskip

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=1cm and 0.5cm, scale=0.9, transform shape]
		\node[data] (dem) {DTM + Terrain};
		\node[data, right=of dem] (hydro) {Hydrology Layers};
		\node[stage, below=of dem] (feat) {Feature Stack (9 features)};
		\node[ml, below=of feat] (model) {XGBoost Classifier};
		\node[output, right=of model] (risk) {Risk Probability};
		\node[output, above=of risk] (hotspot) {Hotspot Polygons};

		\draw[arrow] (dem) -- (feat);
		\draw[arrow] (hydro) -- (feat);
		\draw[arrow] (feat) -- (model);
		\draw[arrow] (model) -- (risk);
		\draw[arrow] (model) -- (hotspot);
	\end{tikzpicture}
	\caption{Waterlogging Prediction Pipeline}
\end{figure}

\bigskip

\textbf{Label Generation}: Since historical flood data is unavailable, terrain-heuristic pseudo-labels are generated:
\begin{equation}
	\text{Label} = 1 \text{ if } (\text{TWI} \ge 8) \land (\text{TPI} \le -0.3) \land (\text{slope} \le 2^\circ)
\end{equation}

\textbf{Model Training}: XGBoost with:
\begin{itemize}
	\item 500 estimators, max depth 7, learning rate 0.05;
	\item \texttt{scale\_pos\_weight} = 5 for class imbalance;
	\item 5-fold stratified cross-validation with ROC-AUC metric.
\end{itemize}

Output is a probability raster (0--1) and polygon hotspots (GeoPackage).

\subsection{Stage 6: Drainage Network Design}

The drainage design pipeline:

\bigskip

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=1.2cm and 0.5cm, scale=0.85, transform shape]
		\node[data] (hotspot) {Waterlogging Hotspots};
		\node[data, right=of hotspot] (depress) {Depression Centroids};
		\node[stage, below=of hotspot] (graph) {Graph Construction (NetworkX)};
		\node[stage, right=of graph] (mst) {MST Optimization};
		\node[stage, right=of mst] (manning) {Manning's Sizing};
		\node[output, right=of manning] (design) {Drainage Design (GPKG)};

		\draw[arrow] (hotspot) -- (graph);
		\draw[arrow] (depress) -- (graph);
		\draw[arrow] (graph) -- (mst);
		\draw[arrow] (mst) -- (manning);
		\draw[arrow] (manning) -- (design);
	\end{tikzpicture}
	\caption{Drainage Network Design Pipeline}
\end{figure}

\bigskip

\begin{enumerate}
	\item \textbf{Demand node identification}: Waterlogging hotspots + depression centroids;
	\item \textbf{Outlet identification}: Village boundary edge cells;
	\item \textbf{Graph construction}: NetworkX graph weighted by excavation cost (proportional to length);
	\item \textbf{MST optimization}: Kruskal's algorithm for minimum-cost spanning network;
	\item \textbf{Hydraulic sizing}: Manning's equation for trapezoidal channels;
	\item \textbf{Channel type selection}: Earthen (low cost), concrete (high flow), or pipe (constrained areas);
	\item \textbf{Cost estimation}: INR per metre by channel type.
\end{enumerate}

Peak discharge is estimated using the Rational Method:
\begin{equation}
	Q_{design} = C \cdot i \cdot A
\end{equation}
where $C$ = 0.65 (runoff coefficient), $i$ = 50 mm/hr (10-year design storm), and $A$ = catchment area in km$^2$.

Outputs include drainage channel polylines with design parameters and a design summary.

