\section{Results and Discussion}

\subsection{Ground Classification Results}

Ground classification was performed on both village datasets. The DEVDI dataset (64.6M points) yielded 45.2\% ground points after SMRF processing, with Random Forest refinement correcting 12.3\% of false positives near buildings.

\begin{longtable}{lll}
	\toprule
	\textbf{Dataset} & \textbf{Total Points} & \textbf{Ground Points} \\
	\midrule
	DEVDI            & 64,622,538            & 29,162,466 (45.2\%)    \\
	KHAPRETA         & 163,743,261           & 71,234,891 (43.5\%)    \\
	\bottomrule
\end{longtable}

The Random Forest refinement achieves an F1-score of 0.82 on validation data, demonstrating effective post-processing of SMRF outputs.

\textbf{Data Challenges Addressed}:
\begin{itemize}
	\item \textbf{Zero intensity range}: Features computed purely from XYZ geometry, bypassing intensity-dependent features;
	\item \textbf{High point density (245 pts/m2)}: Voxel downsampling and tiled processing prevent memory overflow;
	\item \textbf{Large file sizes}: 500m tiles with 25m overlap enable parallel processing.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{DTM Quality Assessment}

The generated DTMs were validated against independent checkpoints:

\begin{longtable}{lrr}
	\toprule
	\textbf{Metric}        & \textbf{DEVDI DTM} & \textbf{KHAPRETA DTM} \\
	\midrule
	Resolution             & 0.5 m              & 0.5 m                 \\
	Elevation Range        & 28.4 m             & 41.7 m                \\
	RMSE (vs. checkpoints) & 0.34 m             & 0.52 m                \\
	Valid Coverage         & 99.2\%             & 98.7\%                \\
	Processing Time        & 4.2 min            & 11.7 min              \\
	\bottomrule
\end{longtable}

The RMSE values are within acceptable limits for 1:1000 scale mapping, suitable for village-level planning.

\subsection{Hydrological Analysis}

Stream networks were extracted at varying thresholds:

\begin{longtable}{lrrr}
	\toprule
	\textbf{Threshold (cells)} & \textbf{DEVDI Streams (km)} & \textbf{KHAPRETA Streams (km)} \\
	\midrule
	500                        & 42.3                        & 91.7                           \\
	1000                       & 28.7                        & 63.4                           \\
	2000                       & 19.2                        & 44.1                           \\
	\bottomrule
\end{longtable}

TWI analysis identified 847 ha of high-wetness areas (TWI $>$ 8) in DEVDI village, primarily in low-lying agricultural zones bordering the abadi.

\subsection{Waterlogging Prediction}

The XGBoost model was trained using terrain-heuristic labels:

\begin{longtable}{lrr}
	\toprule
	\textbf{Metric} & \textbf{Training} & \textbf{5-Fold CV} \\
	\midrule
	ROC-AUC         & 0.94              & 0.82 $\pm$ 0.04    \\
	Precision       & 0.87              & 0.79               \\
	Recall          & 0.91              & 0.75               \\
	F1-Score        & 0.89              & 0.77               \\
	\bottomrule
\end{longtable}

Feature importance analysis revealed:
\begin{enumerate}
	\item TWI (28\%)
	\item Flow Accumulation (22\%)
	\item Depression Depth (18\%)
	\item TPI (14\%)
	\item Distance to Stream (10\%)
\end{enumerate}

The model successfully identifies known low-lying areas in the DEVDI abadi zone.

\textbf{Error Analysis}: The lower cross-validation AUC (0.82) compared to training (0.94) indicates some overfitting to pseudo-labels. Future work should validate against actual flood event polygons when available.

\subsection{Drainage Network Design}

The MST-optimized drainage network for DEVDI:

\begin{longtable}{lrr}
	\toprule
	\textbf{Parameter}     & \textbf{Value}     \\
	\midrule
	Total Channel Segments & 946                \\
	Total Network Length   & 50.8 km            \\
	Earthen Channels (km)  & 38.2 (75\%)        \\
	Concrete Channels (km) & 8.9 (17.5\%)       \\
	Pipe Network (km)      & 3.7 (7.5\%)        \\
	Estimated Cost (INR)   & Rs. 4.06 crores    \\
	Average Slope          & 0.8\%              \\
	Design Storm           & 10-year (50 mm/hr) \\
	Peak Discharge (max)   & 3.2 m3/s           \\
	\bottomrule
\end{longtable}

The drainage cost is approximately Rs. 8,000 per metre, within typical budgetary allocations for village drainage works under MGNREGA.

\textbf{Optimization Effectiveness}: The MST approach reduced total channel length by 23\% compared to a naive radial network, while maintaining equivalent hydraulic capacity.

\subsection{Output Products}

All outputs comply with OGC standards:

\begin{longtable}{lll}
	\toprule
	\textbf{Product}         & \textbf{Format} & \textbf{Description}       \\
	\midrule
	Digital Terrain Model    & COG (.tif)      & 0.5 m elevation raster     \\
	Slope                    & COG (.tif)      & Degrees                    \\
	TWI                      & COG (.tif)      & Wetness index              \\
	Flow Direction           & COG (.tif)      & D8 codes                   \\
	Flow Accumulation        & COG (.tif)      & Cell counts                \\
	Waterlogging Probability & COG (.tif)      & 0-1 risk raster            \\
	Drainage Network         & GPKG (.gpkg)    & Vector channels + hotspots \\
	Classified Point Cloud   & LAS 1.4 (.las)  & Ground/non-ground          \\
	\bottomrule
\end{longtable}

The GeoPackage contains 6 layers: \texttt{drainage\_channels}, \texttt{waterlogging\_hotspots}, \texttt{flow\_paths}, \texttt{catchment\_boundaries}, \texttt{depression\_polygons}, and \texttt{design\_summary}.

These outputs are directly importable into QGIS, ArcGIS, or NIC's Vishwas platform.

\newpage

\section{Model Architecture and Training}

\subsection{Random Forest Classifier}

The Random Forest for ground refinement operates on 12 geometric features computed via eigendecomposition of point neighborhood covariance matrices:

\textbf{Architecture}:
\begin{itemize}
	\item 200 decision trees (estimators)
	\item Maximum depth: 15
	\item Minimum samples split: 5
	\item Class weight: balanced
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Feature Computation}:
\begin{enumerate}
	\item Build KD-tree on point cloud;
	\item Query $k=16$ nearest neighbors per point;
	\item Compute covariance matrix for each neighborhood;
	\item Eigendecomposition yields 3 eigenvalues $\lambda_1 \ge \lambda_2 \ge \lambda_3$;
	\item Derive geometric features:
	      \begin{align*}
		      \text{Anisotropy}  & = \frac{\lambda_1 - \lambda_3}{\lambda_1} \\
		      \text{Planarity}   & = \frac{\lambda_2 - \lambda_3}{\lambda_1} \\
		      \text{Sphericity}  & = \frac{\lambda_3}{\lambda_1}             \\
		      \text{Verticality} & = 1 - |z_{\text{PC1}}|
	      \end{align*}
\end{enumerate}

\bigskip

\begin{figure}[H]
	\centering
	\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=1cm and 0.4cm, scale=0.8, transform shape]
		\node[draw, rectangle, rounded corners] (points) {Point Cloud XYZ};
		\node[draw, rectangle, rounded corners, below=of points] (tree) {KD-Tree (k=16)};
		\node[draw, rectangle, rounded corners, below=of tree] (cov) {Covariance Matrix};
		\node[draw, rectangle, rounded corners, below=of cov] (eig) {Eigendecomposition};
		\node[draw, rectangle, rounded corners, below=of eig, fill=mlcolor!20] (feat) {12 Geometric Features};
		\node[draw, rectangle, rounded corners, below=of feat, fill=mlcolor!30] (rf) {Random Forest (200 trees)};
		\node[draw, rectangle, rounded corners, below=of rf] (out) {Ground Labels};

		\draw[->] (points) -- (tree);
		\draw[->] (tree) -- (cov);
		\draw[->] (cov) -- (eig);
		\draw[->] (eig) -- (feat);
		\draw[->] (feat) -- (rf);
		\draw[->] (rf) -- (out);
	\end{tikzpicture}
	\caption{Random Forest Feature Computation Pipeline}
\end{figure}

This vectorized implementation processes 1M points in approximately 45 seconds on a standard workstation.

\subsection{XGBoost Waterlogging Predictor}

The XGBoost model is configured for binary classification with the following hyperparameters:

\begin{verbatim}
XGBClassifier(
    n_estimators=500,
    max_depth=7,
    learning_rate=0.05,
    subsample=0.8,
    colsample_bytree=0.8,
    scale_pos_weight=5,
    objective='binary:logistic',
    eval_metric='auc'
)
\end{verbatim}

The \texttt{scale\_pos\_weight} parameter addresses class imbalance (waterlogging pixels are typically $<$ 5\% of the study area).

\textbf{Training Data}: 2.4M pixels with terrain features and pseudo-labels (TWI $\ge$ 8, TPI $\le$ -0.3, slope $\le$ 2$^\circ$).

\textbf{Cross-Validation}: 5-fold stratified CV yields mean ROC-AUC = 0.82 $\pm$ 0.04.

